<div class="text" id="centre_col">
<p><a name="top"></a></p>
<H1>ESSUM34310 - Linkage to Savings (Arrangement): Bonus date</H1><BR><P>Savings contracts provide for contributions to be made over a period of 3 or 5 years. Contributions can either be </P>
<UL>
<LI class="filledcircle">withdrawn at that date (the "standard" bonus date) with a standard bonus (see ESSUM34170),  or</LI>
<LI class="filledcircle">in the case of 5 year contracts only, left in the scheme for a further two years during which interest continues to accrue and a maximum bonus is payable at the 7 year point (the "maximum" bonus date) instead.</LI>
</UL>
<P>The scheme must contain a provision preventing the exercise of options before the bonus date, other than in the circumstances set out in paragraphs 32 - 34 &amp; 37. Paragraph 30 defines the bonus date as the date on which repayments under the savings contract are due, this being the earliest date on which the bonus ("maximum" or "standard") appropriate to the option is payable (paragraph 30 (4) (b)).</P>
<P>The scheme must provide that the aggregate exercise price of an option will equal the eventual repayments under the related savings arrangement (paragraph 25).</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>For this purpose:<BR></BLOCKQUOTE>
<UL>
<LI class="filledcircle">the "repayments" may be taken as including the "maximum" bonus, or a “lesser” bonus (meaning either the “standard” bonus or no bonus (paragraph 26 (2)),  but </LI>
<LI class="filledcircle">the scheme rules must make it clear that the decision on what is to be included must be taken when the option is granted (paragraph 26 (3)).</LI>
</UL>
<P>It is acceptable for scheme rules to provide that the bonus date for all options granted under the scheme is the “standard” bonus date, or, in the case of 5 year contracts, to provide that the bonus date for all options granted under the scheme is the “maximum” bonus date.</P>
<P>Paragraph 30 refers to rights of exercise on the bonus date and not later than 6 months after that date.  In the case of 5 year contracts arrangements designed to give employees a choice, after their options have been granted, of 5 or 7 year bonus dates are not acceptable.  Nor is it acceptable to grant 5 and 7 year options in parallel to each other, linking both to the same savings contract, with one lapsing when the other is exercised. </P>
<P>The ancillary scheme documents must also make it clear which of the bonus alternatives in the 5 year contract applies to the option concerned. If the 5 year contract applies and the individual chooses not to exercise the option on the “standard” bonus date the option will lapse 6 months after that date.</P>
<P>If the repayment, on which the option is based, has been taken to include the maximum bonus, the earliest date on which the option can be exercised in normal circumstances will be the 7 year point when the maximum bonus is payable.  In other cases the date repayment is due will be the date on which the standard bonus is payable (3 or 5 years depending on which savings contract has been entered into).</P><BR><div class="manual-nav">
